{"title_page": "The Hollywood Ten", "text_new": "{{About|the 1950 American documentary|the ten 1947 Hollywood blacklistees|Hollywood Ten}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Hollywood Ten\n| image          = Hollywoodtenimage.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| border         =\n| caption        = Promotional image\n| director       = [[John Berry (film director)|John Berry]]\n| producer       = John Berry\n| writer         = John Berry\n| narrator       = Colin Chandler\n| distributor    = [[The Criterion Collection]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1950|1|15|United States}}\n| runtime        = 15 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n}}\n'''''The Hollywood Ten''''' is a 1950 American [[16mm]] short [[documentary film]]. In the film, each member of the [[Hollywood Ten]] made a short speech denouncing [[McCarthyism]] and the [[Hollywood blacklist]]ing.\n\nThe film was directed by [[John Berry (film director)|John Berry]]. After being named a communist by fellow director and former party member [[Edward Dmytryk]],<ref name=LAT>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/dec/01/news/mn-39376|title=John Berry; Blacklisted Film Director Relocated Overseas|last=Oliver|first=Myrna|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 1, 1999|accessdate=January 30, 2016}}</ref> one of the Hollywood Ten, and ex-[[Communist Party USA|Communist Party]] member [[Frank Tuttle]],<ref>{{cite book|last=McBride|first=Joseph|title=Frank Capra: The Catastrophe of Success|year=1992|publisher=Simon & Schuster|location=New York|isbn=0-671-73494-6|pages=[https://archive.org/details/frankcapracatast00mcbr/page/597 597]|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/frankcapracatast00mcbr/page/597}}</ref> Berry was unable to find work again in Hollywood after 1951, and left for France.<ref>[http://www.ironweedfilms.com/films/hollywoodten ''The Hollywood Ten''] on the ''Ironweed'' web site. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060425110827/http://www.ironweedfilms.com/films/hollywoodten |date=April 25, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nThe documentary is available on the DVD releases of ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]''<ref>[http://www.criterion.com/films/449-spartacus ''The Criterion Collection'']. ''Spartacus'' (1960). Accessed: June 28, 2013.</ref> and ''[[Salt of the Earth (1954 film)|Salt of the Earth]]''.\n\n==Featuring==\n* [[Herbert J. Biberman]]\n* [[Lester Cole]]\n* [[Edward Dmytryk]]\n* [[Ring Lardner Jr.]]\n* [[John Howard Lawson]]\n* [[Albert Maltz]]\n* [[Samuel Ornitz]]\n* [[Adrian Scott]]\n* [[Dalton Trumbo]]\n* [[Alvah Bessie]]\n\n==Release==\n''The Hollywood Ten'' was shown at the [[Museum of Modern Art]] in New York City as a part of the \"Carte Blanche\" series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/1993/voices/columns/berry-career-inevitably-comes-back-to-the-blacklist-115665/|title=Berry career inevitably comes back to the blacklist|last=McCarthy|first=Todd|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=1993-11-04|accessdate=2015-02-15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Caballero, Raymond. ''McCarthyism vs. Clinton Jencks.'' Norman: University of Oklahoma Press, 2019.\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0172563|title=The Hollywood Ten}}\n* [http://www.lib.berkeley.edu/MRC/blacklist.html ''The Hollywood Ten''] bios at [[University of California, Berkeley]], Library\n* [http://www.writing.upenn.edu/~afilreis/50s/berry-obit.html John Berry]'s obituary in [[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]\n* {{YouTube|P3MlaFIzCw8|''The Hollywood Ten'' trailer}}\n* {{YouTube|taancRcLQ8o|''The Hollywood Ten'' film}}\n\n{{John Berry (film director)}}\n{{Hollywood Ten}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hollywood Ten, The}}\n[[Category:1950 films]]\n[[Category:1950s documentary films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American documentary films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Black-and-white documentary films]]\n[[Category:Documentary films about American politics]]\n[[Category:Films directed 